### Finding 6: Your Supabase anon key grants full access without RLS

**What's happening — think of it like this:**

Your app communicates with your database using two pieces of information:
1. **Supabase URL**: `https://lvwuhzurgnhdzwldnkyx.supabase.co` — this is like the address of your house
2. **Anon key**: `sb_publishable_kNdXpCUWaig2tNLsbxDs3w_B-VisW5u` — this is like a key you give to delivery drivers

Both are embedded in your frontend JavaScript. **Anyone who visits your website can see them** by opening DevTools → Sources → searching for "supabase."

The anon key is **designed** to be public — Supabase expects this. The protection is supposed to come from **Row-Level Security (RLS)** — database rules that say "this user can only see their own data."

**But you haven't enabled RLS.**

Without RLS, the anon key gives full access to every row in every table. It's like giving a delivery driver a master key to every room in your house.

**Why it's dangerous — a practical attack:**

Any visitor to your site can open the browser console and run:

```js
import { createClient } from 'https://esm.sh/@supabase/supabase-js';

// These values are visible in your JS bundle
const sb = createClient(
  'https://lvwuhzurgnhdzwldnkyx.supabase.co',
  'sb_publishable_kNdXpCUWaig2tNLsbxDs3w_B-VisW5u'
);

// Read ALL users' data
const { data } = await sb.from('profiles').select('*');
console.log(data); // Every user's email, name, social links

// Read ALL prompts (including other users' private ones)
const { data: prompts } = await sb.from('prompts').select('*');

// Delete someone else's prompts
await sb.from('prompts').delete().eq('created_by', 'some-other-user-id');

// Modify someone's profile
await sb.from('profiles').update({ full_name: 'HACKED' }).eq('username', 'victim');
```

**This is not theoretical.** If your app is deployed, this works right now.

**Severity:** 🔴 **CRITICAL — this is the #1 security issue in your entire app**

**Fix — Enable Row-Level Security (30 minutes):**

Go to Supabase Dashboard → SQL Editor → run ALL of these:

```sql
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
-- STEP 1: Enable RLS (blocks ALL access by default)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════

ALTER TABLE profiles ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
ALTER TABLE prompts ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
-- STEP 2: Profiles policies
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════

-- Anyone can VIEW profiles (needed for public vaults)
CREATE POLICY "Anyone can read profiles"
  ON profiles FOR SELECT
  USING (true);

-- Users can only UPDATE their own profile
CREATE POLICY "Users update own profile"
  ON profiles FOR UPDATE
  USING (auth.uid() = id)
  WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = id);

-- Users can only INSERT their own profile (signup)
CREATE POLICY "Users insert own profile"
  ON profiles FOR INSERT
  WITH CHECK (auth.uid() = id);

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
-- STEP 3: Prompts policies
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════

-- Users can see their OWN prompts (all of them)
CREATE POLICY "Users read own prompts"
  ON prompts FOR SELECT
  USING (created_by = auth.uid());

-- Anyone can see PUBLIC prompts (for public/shared vaults)
CREATE POLICY "Anyone reads public prompts"
  ON prompts FOR SELECT
  USING (is_public = true);

-- Users can only CREATE prompts for themselves
CREATE POLICY "Users create own prompts"
  ON prompts FOR INSERT
  WITH CHECK (created_by = auth.uid());

-- Users can only UPDATE their own prompts
CREATE POLICY "Users update own prompts"
  ON prompts FOR UPDATE
  USING (created_by = auth.uid())
  WITH CHECK (created_by = auth.uid());

-- Users can only DELETE their own prompts
CREATE POLICY "Users delete own prompts"
  ON prompts FOR DELETE
  USING (created_by = auth.uid());
```

After running this, the exact same anon key now only allows users to access their own data. The key didn't change — but the **database now enforces rules**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> After enabling RLS, test your entire app. Some features may break if they relied on reading other users' non-public data — particularly **SharedVault**, which currently reads ALL prompts from another user regardless of `is_public`. Fix that query first.

