### Finding 7: SharedVault exposes private prompts

**What's happening:**

[SharedVault.jsx:76-80](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/SharedVault.jsx#L76-L80):
```js
const { data, error } = await supabase
  .from('prompts')
  .select('*')
  .eq('created_by', profile.id)
  // ← No .eq('is_public', true) filter!
  .order('created_at', { ascending: false });
```

Compare with PublicVault, which correctly filters:
```js
.eq('created_by', profile.id)
.eq('is_public', true)          // ← PublicVault does this
```

SharedVault shows **every** prompt the user has created, including ones they marked as private.

**Why it's dangerous:**

If User A has 50 prompts and marked 10 as private (maybe they contain confidential client information or internal processes), anyone with User A's vault link can see all 50 — including the private 10.

**Severity:** 🔴 **CRITICAL — active privacy leak**

**Fix — one line:**

```js
// SharedVault.jsx line 79 — add the filter
.eq('created_by', profile.id)
.eq('is_public', true)          // ← ADD THIS LINE
.order('created_at', { ascending: false });
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Design decision needed:** If SharedVault is supposed to show ALL prompts (as a "full vault share"), then it should be a **protected** route that requires the vault owner to explicitly grant access (e.g., with a secret token in the URL). Currently, anyone who knows/guesses a username can see everything.

